e=\"text-align:center;\" {{Party shading/Democratic}}|'''72.5%''' ''687''\n|style=\"text-align:center;|\n|-\n|style=\"text-align:center;\" {{Party shading/Democratic}}|'''[[United States presidential election in Georgia, 1924|1924]]'''\n|style=\"text-align:center;\" {{Party shading/Republican}}|14.1% ''76''\n|style=\"text-align:center;\" {{Party shading/Democratic}}|'''83.0%''' ''449''\n|style=\"text-align:center; background:honeyDew;\"|3.0% ''16''\n|-\n|style=\"text-align:center;\" {{Party shading/Democratic}}|'''[[United States presidential election in Georgia, 1920|1920]]'''\n|style=\"text-align:center;\" {{Party shading/Republican}}|9.2% ''39''\n|style=\"text-align:center;\" {{Party shading/Democratic}}|'''90.9%''' ''387''\n|style=\"text-align:center;|\n|-\n|style=\"text-align:center;\" {{Party shading/Democratic}}|'''[[United States presidential election in Georgia, 1916|1916]]'''\n|style=\"text-align:center;\" {{Party shading/Republican}}|2.0% ''14''\n|style=\"text-align:center;\" {{Party shading/Democratic}}|'''95.3%''' ''673''\n|style=\"text-align:center; background:honeyDew;\"|2.7% ''19''\n|-\n|style=\"text-align:center;\" {{Party shading/Democratic}}|'''[[United States presidential election in Georgia, 1912|1912]]'''\n|style=\"text-align:center;\" {{Party shading/Republican}}|4.6% ''22''\n|style=\"text-align:center;\" {{Party shading/Democratic}}|'''90.9%''' ''440''\n|style=\"text-align:center; background:honeyDew;\"|4.6% ''22''\n|}\n{{Hidden end}}\n\n== See also ==\n{{Portal|State of Georgia}}\n* [[Central Savannah River Area]]\n* [[National Register of Historic Places listings in Burke County, Georgia]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* Albert M. Hillhouse. ''A History of Burke County, Georgia, 1777-1950.'' Reprint Company and Magnolia Press, 1985.\n* [http://www.burkecounty-ga.gov/ Burke County Official Website]\n* [http://www.burkeacademy.org/ Edmund Burke Academy]\n* [http://burkechamber.org/ Burke County Chamber of Commerce]\n* [http://georgiainfo.galileo.usg.edu/topics/historical_markers/county/burke/burke-county Burke County] historical marker\n* [http://georgiainfo.galileo.usg.edu/topics/historical_markers/county/burke/botsford-church-1773 Botsford Church] historical marker\n\n{{Geographic Location\n|Centre    = Burke County, Georgia\n|North     = [[Richmond County, Georgia|Richmond County]]\n|Northeast = [[Aiken County, South Carolina]] and [[Barnwell County, South Carolina]]\n|East      = [[Allendale County, South Carolina]]\n|Southeast = [[Screven County, Georgia|Screven County]]\n|South     = [[Jenkins County, Georgia|Jenkins County]]\n|Southwest = [[Emanuel County, Georgia|Emanuel County]]\n|West      = [[Jefferson County, Georgia|Jefferson County]]\n|Northwest =\n}}\n\n{{Burke County, Georgia}}\n{{Central Savannah River Area}}\n{{CSRAUniCol}}\n{{Georgia (U.S. state)}}\n{{Coord|33.06|-82.00|display=title|type:adm2nd_region:US-GA_source:UScensus1990}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Burke County, Georgia| ]]\n[[Category:1777 establishments in Georgia (U.S. state)]]\n[[Category:Populated places established in 1777]]\n[[Category:Georgia (U.S. state) counties]]\n[[Category:Augusta metropolitan area]]\n", "text_old": "{{Short description|County in Georgia, United States}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=November 2019}}\n{{Infobox U.S. county\n| county = Burke County\n| state = Georgia\n| seal =\n| founded = 1777\n| seat wl= Waynesboro\n| largest city wl= Waynesboro\n| area_total_sq_mi = 835\n| area_land_sq_mi = 827\n| area_water_sq_mi = 8.0\n| area percentage = 1.0%\n| census estimate yr = 2018\n| pop = 22,423\n| density_sq_mi = 27\n| time zone = Eastern\n| web =http://www.burkecounty-ga.gov/\n| ex image = Burke County Courthouse; Waynesboro, Georgia; April 16, 2011.JPG\n| ex image cap = Burke County courthouse in Waynesboro, Georgia\n| named for = [[Edmund Burke]]<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.georgiaencyclopedia.org/nge/Article.jsp?id=h-2301 | title=Burke County | publisher=[[Georgia Humanities Council]] | work=[[New Georgia Encyclopedia]] | date=November 11, 2011 | accessdate=August 8, 2012 | author=Cooksey, Elizabeth B.}}</ref>\n| district = 12th\n}}\n'''Burke County''' is a [[County (United States)|county]] located along the eastern border of the [[U.S. state]] of [[Georgia (U.S. state)|Georgia]] in the Piedmont. As of the [[2010 United States Census|2010 census]], the population was 23,316.<ref name=\"QF\">{{cite web|title=State & County QuickFacts|url=https://www.census.gov/quickfacts/table/PST045216/13033|publisher=United States Census Bureau|accessdate=February 15, 2014}}</ref> The [[county seat]] is [[Waynesboro, Georgia|Waynesboro]].<ref name=\"GR6\">{{cite web|url=http://www.naco.org/Counties/Pages/FindACounty.aspx |accessdate=2011-06-07 |title=Find a County |publisher=National Association of Counties |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110531210815/http://www.naco.org/Counties/Pages/FindACounty.aspx |archivedate=2011-05-31 }}</ref>\n\nBurke County is part of the [[Augusta, Georgia|Augusta-Richmond County]], GA-[[South Carolina|SC]] [[Augusta, Georgia metropolitan area|Metropolitan Statistical Area]].\n\n== History ==\nBurke County is an original county of Georgia, created February 5, 1777.<ref>{{cite book | url=http://www.kenkrakow.com/gpn/b.pdf | title=Georgia Place-Names: Their History and Origins | publisher=Winship Press | author=Krakow, Kenneth K. | year=1975 | location=Macon, GA | pages=29 | isbn=0-915430-00-2}}</ref> In 1779, Col. John Twiggs and brothers Col. William Few and Benjamin Few, along with 250 men, defeated British in the Battle of Burke Jail.\n\nBurke County is located within the CSRA (the Central Savannah River Area). During the antebellum period, it was developed by slave labor for large cotton plantations. The county was majority African American in population in this period, as slaveholders needed high numbers of slaves for laborers to cultivate and process cotton.\n\nThe military tradition continued during the American Civil War, when Burke County provided volunteers for numerous units: the 2nd Regiment Georgia Infantry Company D (Burke Sharpshooters), 3rd Regiment Georgia Infantry Company A (Burke Guards), 32nd Regiment Georgia Infantry Company C (Williams Volunteers), 32nd Regiment Georgia Infantry Company K (Alexander Greys), 48th Regiment Georgia Infantry Company D (Burke Volunteers), Cobb's Legion Infantry company E (Poythress Volunteers), and the Cobb's Legion Cavalry Company F (Grubb's Hussars).\n\nAgriculture continued as the basis of the economy for decades after the [[American Civil War]], when most [[freedmen]] worked as sharecroppers or tenant farmers. Cotton was the major commodity crop.<ref>[http://www.csrardc.org/]</ref> In the early 20th century, mechanization of agriculture caused many African-American farm workers to lose their jobs.\n\nAs can be seen from the census tables below, the county lost population from 1910-1920, and from 1930-1970. Part of the decline was related to the [[Great Migration (African American)|Great Migration]], as millions of African Americans left the rural South and [[Jim Crow]] oppression for jobs and opportunities in industrial cities of the Midwest, North. From World War II on, primary migration destinations were West Coast cities because of the buildup of the defense industry. In addition, whites left rural areas for industrial jobs in the North, in cities such as Chicago and Detroit.\n\n== Geography ==\nAccording to the [[U.S. Census Bureau]], the county has a total area of {{convert|835|sqmi}}, of which {{convert|827|sqmi}} is land and {{convert|8.0|sqmi}} (1.0%) is water.<ref name=\"GR1\">{{cite web|url=https://www.census.gov/geo/www/gazetteer/gazette.html|publisher=[[United States Census Bureau]]|accessdate=2011-04-23|date=2011-02-12|title=US Gazetteer files: 2010, 2000, and 1990}}</ref> It is the second-largest county by area in Georgia.\n\nThe southern half of Burke County, defined by a line running along [[Georgia State Route 80|State Route 80]] to [[Waynesboro, Georgia|Waynesboro]], then southeast  to east of [[Perkins, Georgia|Perkins]], is located in the Upper [[Ogeechee River]] sub-basin of the Ogeechee River basin.  North of Waynesboro, and bordered on the north by a line running from [[Keysville, Georgia|Keysville]] southeast to [[Girard, Georgia|Girard]], the territory is part of the [[Brier Creek (Savannah River)|Brier Creek]] sub-basin of the [[Savannah River]] basin. The most northern sliver of Burke County is located in the Middle [[Savannah River]] sub-basin of the same Savannah River basin.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.gaswcc.org/maps/ |title=Georgia Soil and Water Conservation Commission Interactive Mapping Experience |publisher=Georgia Soil and Water Conservation Commission |accessdate=2015-11-21}}</ref>\n\n=== Major highways ===\n{{div col|colwidth=22em}}\n* [[File:US 25.svg|20px]] [[U.S. Route 25 in Georgia|U.S. Route 25]]\n* [[File:Bypass plate.png|20px]]<br />[[File:US 25.svg|20px]] [[U.S. Route 25 Bypass (Waynesboro, Georgia)|U.S. Route 25 Bypass]]\n* [[File:Georgia 17.svg|20px]] [[Georgia State Route 17|State Route 17]]\n* [[File:Georgia 23.svg|20px]] [[Georgia State Route 23|State Route 23]]\n* [[File:Georgia 24.svg|20px]] [[Georgia State Route 24|State Route 24]]\n* [[File:Georgia 56.svg|20px]] [[Georgia State Route 56|State Route 56]]\n* [[File:Georgia 56 Spur.svg|20px]] [[Georgia State Route 56 Spur (Burke County)|State Route 56 Spur]]\n* [[File:Georgia 78.svg|20px]] [[Georgia State Route 78|State Route 78]]\n* [[File:Georgia 80.svg|20px]] [[Georgia State Route 80|State Route 80]]\n* [[File:Georgia 88.svg|20px]] [[Georgia State Route 88|State Route 88]]\n* [[File:Georgia 121.svg|20px]] [[Georgia State Route 121|State Route 121]]\n* [[File:Georgia 121 Bypass.svg|20px]] [[Georgia State Route 121 Bypass (Waynesboro)|State Route 121 Bypass]]\n* [[File:Georgia 305.svg|20px]] [[Georgia State Route 305|State Route 305]]\n* [[File:Georgia 565.svg|20px]] [[Savannah River Parkway]]\n{{div col end}}\n\n=== Adjacent counties ===\n{{div col}}\n* [[Richmond County, GA|Richmond County]] (north)\n* [[Aiken County, South Carolina|Aiken County]], [[South Carolina]] (northeast)\n* [[Barnwell County, South Carolina|Barnwell County]], [[South Carolina]] (east-northeast)\n* [[Allendale County, South Carolina|Allendale County]], [[South Carolina]] (east)\n* [[Screven County, GA|Screven County]] (southeast)\n* [[Jenkins County, GA|Jenkins County]] (south)\n* [[Emanuel County, GA|Emanuel County]] (southwest)\n* [[Jefferson County, GA|Jefferson County]] (west)\n{{div col end}}\n\n== Demographics ==\n{{US Census population\n|1790= 9467\n|1800= 9504\n|1810= 10858\n|1820= 11577\n|1830= 11833\n|1840= 13176\n|1850= 16100\n|1860= 17165\n|1870= 17679\n|1880= 27128\n|1890= 28501\n|1900= 30165\n|1910= 27268\n|1920= 30836\n|1930= 29224\n|1940= 26520\n|1950= 23458\n|1960= 20596\n|1970= 18255\n|1980= 19349\n|1990= 20579\n|2000= 22243\n|2010= 23316\n|estyear=2018\n|estimate=22423\n|estref=<ref name=\"USCensusEst2018\">{{cite web|url=https://www.census.gov/programs-surveys/popest/data/tables.2018.html|title=Population and Housing Unit Estimates|accessdate=July 30, 2019}}</ref>\n|align-fn=center\n|footnote=U.S. Decennial Census<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.census.gov/prod/www/decennial.html|title=U.S. Decennial Census|publisher=United States Census Bureau|accessdate=June 18, 2014|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150426102944/http://www.census.gov/prod/www/decennial.html|archivedate=April 26, 2015}}</ref><br />1790-1960<ref>{{cite web|url=http://mapserver.lib.virginia.edu|title=Historical Census Browser|publisher=University of Virginia Library|accessdate=June 18, 2014}}</ref> 1900-1990<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.census.gov/population/cencounts/ga190090.txt|title=Population of Counties by Decennial Census: 1900 to 1990|publisher=United States Census Bureau|accessdate=June 18, 2014}}</ref><br />1990-2000<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.census.gov/population/www/cen2000/briefs/phc-t4/tables/tab02.pdf|title=Census 2000 PHC-T-4. Ranking Tables for Counties: 1990 and 2000|publisher=United States Census Bureau|accessdate=June 18, 2014}}</ref>\n}}\n\n===2010 census===\nAs of the [[2010 United States Census]], there were 23,316&nbsp;people, 8,533&nbsp;households, and 6,110&nbsp;families living in the county.<ref name=\"census-dp1\">{{cite web\n  |url=http://factfinder.census.gov/bkmk/table/1.0/en/DEC/10_DP/DPDP1/0500000US13033\n  |title=DP-1 Profile of General Population and Housing Characteristics: 2010 Demographic Profile Data\n  |accessdate=2015-12-27\n  |publisher=[[United States Census Bureau]]\n  |archive-url=https://archive.today/20200213011840/http://factfinder.census.gov/bkmk/table/1.0/en/DEC/10_DP/DPDP1/0500000US13033\n  |archive-date=February 13, 2020\n  |url-status=dead\n  }}</ref> The population density was {{convert|28.2|PD/sqmi}}. There were 9,865 housing units at an average density of {{convert|11.9|/sqmi}}.<ref name=\"census-density\">{{cite web\n  |url=http://factfinder.census.gov/bkmk/table/1.0/en/DEC/10_SF1/GCTPH1.CY07/0500000US13033\n  |accessdate=2015-12-27\n  |title=Population, Housing Units, Area, and Density: 2010 - County\n  |publisher=[[United States Census Bureau]]\n  |archive-url=https://archive.today/20200213184138/http://factfinder.census.gov/bkmk/table/1.0/en/DEC/10_SF1/GCTPH1.CY07/0500000US13033\n  |archive-date=February 13, 2020\n  |url-status=dead\n  }}</ref>\nAs of the [[2010 United States Census]], there were 23,316 people living in the county. 49.5% were [[African American|Black or African American]], 47.5% [[White American|White]], 0.3% [[Asian American|Asian]], 0.2% [[Native Americans in the United States|Native American]], 0.1% [[Pacific Islands American|Pacific Islander]], 1.1% from some other race and 1.3% [[Multiracial American|from two or more races]]. 2.6% were [[Hispanic and Latino Americans|Hispanic or Latino]] (of any race).<ref>2010 census report for Burke County, Georgia</ref>\n\nIn terms of ancestry, 49.5% have some African ancestry, 11.0% identify as of [[Americans|American]], 9.3% are [[Irish people|Irish]], 5.5% were [[English people|English]], and 5.1% were [[Germans|German]].<ref name=\"census-dp2\">{{cite web\n  |url=http://factfinder.census.gov/bkmk/table/1.0/en/ACS/10_5YR/DP02/0500000US13033\n  |title=DP02 SELECTED SOCIAL CHARACTERISTICS IN THE UNITED STATES \u2013 2006-2010 American Community Survey 5-Year Estimates\n  |accessdate=2015-12-27\n  |publisher=[[United States Census Bureau]]\n  |archive-url=https://archive.today/20200213011550/http://factfinder.census.gov/bkmk/table/1.0/en/ACS/10_5YR/DP02/0500000US13033\n  |archive-date=February 13, 2020\n  |url-status=dead\n  }}</ref>\n\nOf the 8,533&nbsp;households, 39.0% had children under the age of 18 living with them, 42.4% were married couples living together, 24.1% had a female householder with no husband present, 28.4% were non-families, and 24.3% of all households were made up of individuals. The average household size was 2.70 and the average family size was 3.20. The median age was 35.9 years.<ref name=\"census-dp1\"/>\n\nThe median income for a household in the county was $33,155 and the median income for a family was $41,659. Males had a median income of $37,061 versus $24,952 for females. The per capita income for the county was $15,934. About 20.0% of families and 25.7% of the population were below the [[poverty line]], including 38.0% of those under age 18 and 16.2% of those age 65 or over.<ref name=\"census-dp3\">{{cite web\n  |url=http://factfinder.census.gov/bkmk/table/1.0/en/ACS/10_5YR/DP03/0500000US13033\n  |title=DP03 SELECTED ECONOMIC CHARACTERISTICS \u2013 2006-2010 American Community Survey 5-Year Estimates\n  |accessdate=2015-12-27\n  |publisher=[[United States Census Bureau]]\n  |archive-url=https://archive.today/20200213021325/http://factfinder.census.gov/bkmk/table/1.0/en/ACS/10_5YR/DP03/0500000US13033\n  |archive-date=February 13, 2020\n  |url-status=dead\n  }}</ref>\n\n===2000 census===\nAs of the [[census]]<ref name=\"GR8\">{{cite web |url=http://factfinder2.census.gov |publisher=[[United States Census Bureau]] |accessdate=2011-05-14 |title=American FactFinder |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130911234518/http://factfinder2.census.gov/ |archivedate=2013-09-11 }}</ref> of 2000, there were 22,243 people, 7,934 households, and 5,799 families living in the county.  The [[population density]] was 27 people per square mile (10/km\u00b2).  There were 8,842 housing units at an average density of 11 per square&nbsp;mile (4/km\u00b2).  The racial makeup of the county was 51.00% [[Race (United States Census)|Black]] or [[Race (United States Census)|African American]], 46.90% [[Race (United States Census)|White]],  0.23% [[Race (United States Census)|Native American]], 0.26% [[Race (United States Census)|Asian]], 0.01% [[Race (United States Census)|Pacific Islander]], 0.63% from [[Race (United States Census)|other races]], and 0.97% from two or more races.  1.42% of the population were [[Race (United States Census)|Hispanic]] or [[Race (United States Census)|Latino]] of any race.\n\nThere were 7,934 households out of which 38.40% had children under the age of 18 living with them, 45.40% were [[Marriage|married couples]] living together, 22.80% had a female householder with no husband present, and 26.90% were non-families. 23.60% of all households were made up of individuals and 9.50% had someone living alone who was 65 years of age or older.  The average household size was 2.77 and the average family size was 3.27.\n\nIn the county, the population was spread out with 31.30% under the age of 18, 9.10% from 18 to 24, 27.30% from 25 to 44, 21.40% from 45 to 64, and 10.90% who were 65 years of age or older.  The median age was 33 years. For every 100 females, there were 90.30 males.  For every 100 females age 18 and over, there were 84.60 males.\n\nThe median income for a household in the county was $27,877, and the median income for a family was $31,660. Males had a median income of $29,992 and females had an income of $19,008. The [[per capita income]] for the county was $13,136.  About 23.80% of families and 28.70% of the population were below the [[poverty line]], including 39.00% of those under age 18 and 29.80% of those age 65 or over.\n\n==Education==\n{{Main|Waynesboro, Georgia#Education}}\n\n==Communities==\n* [[Drone, Georgia|Drone]]\n* [[Girard, Georgia|Girard]]\n* [[Gough, Georgia|Gough]]\n* [[Keysville, Georgia|Keysville]]\n* [[Midville, Georgia|Midville]]\n* [[Sardis, Georgia|Sardis]]\n* [[Vidette, Georgia|Vidette]]\n* [[Waynesboro, Georgia|Waynesboro]]\n\n==Politics==\n{{Hidden begin\n|titlestyle = background:#ccccff;\n|title      = Presidential elections results\n}}\n{| align=\"center\" border=\"2\" cellpadding=\"4\" cellspacing=\"0\" style=\"margin: 1em 1em 1em 0; border: 1px #aaa solid; border-collapse: collapse; font-size: 95%;\"\n|+ '''Previous presidential elections results'''<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://uselectionatlas.org/RESULTS|title=Dave Leip's Atlas of U.S. Presidential Elections|last=Leip|first=David|website=uselectionatlas.org|access-date=2018-03-18}}</ref>\n|- bgcolor=lightgrey\n! Year\n! [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]]\n! [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic]]\n! [[Third Party (United States)|Third parties]]\n|-\n|style=\"text-align:center;\" {{Party shading/Democratic}}|'''[[United States presidential election in Georgia, 2016|2016]]'''\n|style=\"text-align:center;\" {{Party shading/Republican}}|48.0% ''4,491''\n|style=\"text-align:center;\" {{Party shading/Democratic}}|'''50.6%''' ''4,731''\n|style=\"text-align:center; background:honeyDew;\"|1.4% ''129''\n|-\n|style=\"text-align:center;\" {{Party shading/Democratic}}|'''[[United States presidential election in Georgia, 2012|2012]]'''\n|style=\"text-align:center;\" {{Party shading/Republican}}|43.9% ''4,