''\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" {{Party shading/Democratic}}|'''50.7%''' ''4,248''\n| style=\"text-align:center; background:honeyDew;\"|6.1% ''511''\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" {{Party shading/Progressive}}|'''[[1912 United States presidential election|1912]]'''\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" {{Party shading/Republican}}|18.3% ''971''\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" {{Party shading/Democratic}}|37.8% ''2,005''\n| style=\"text-align:center; background:honeyDew;\"|'''43.9%''' ''2,330''\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" {{Party shading/Republican}}|'''[[1908 United States presidential election|1908]]'''\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" {{Party shading/Republican}}|'''54.0%''' ''3,049''\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" {{Party shading/Democratic}}|40.5% ''2,290''\n| style=\"text-align:center; background:honeyDew;\"|5.5% ''310''\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" {{Party shading/Republican}}|'''[[1904 United States presidential election|1904]]'''\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" {{Party shading/Republican}}|'''61.9%''' ''3,306''\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" {{Party shading/Democratic}}|28.8% ''1,540''\n| style=\"text-align:center; background:honeyDew;\"|9.3% ''495''\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" {{Party shading/Republican}}|'''[[1900 United States presidential election|1900]]'''\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" {{Party shading/Republican}}|'''50.6%''' ''2,947''\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" {{Party shading/Democratic}}|47.3% ''2,752''\n| style=\"text-align:center; background:honeyDew;\"|2.1% ''120''\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" {{Party shading/Democratic}}|'''[[1896 United States presidential election|1896]]'''\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" {{Party shading/Republican}}|44.9% ''2,414''\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" {{Party shading/Democratic}}|'''54.4%''' ''2,926''\n| style=\"text-align:center; background:honeyDew;\"|0.7% ''35''\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" {{Party shading/Populist}}|'''[[United States presidential election in Kansas, 1892|1892]]'''\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" {{Party shading/Republican}}|48.6% ''2,650''\n|\n| style=\"text-align:center; background:honeyDew;\"|'''51.4%''' ''2,800''\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" {{Party shading/Republican}}|'''[[1888 United States presidential election|1888]]'''\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" {{Party shading/Republican}}|'''55.4%''' ''3,172''\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" {{Party shading/Democratic}}|28.2% ''1,616''\n| style=\"text-align:center; background:honeyDew;\"|16.4% ''942''\n|}\n{{Hidden end}}\n\nLike of most of Kansas\u2019 counties, Butler county is solidly Republican. In 2008, [[John McCain]] carried the county by a nearly two-to-one margin over [[Barack Obama]]. Since 1992, no Democratic candidate has received so much as forty percent of the county's vote.<ref>[http://elections.nytimes.com/2008/results/president/map.html?scp=1&sq=%22election%20map&st=cse The New York Times Electoral Map (Zoom in on Kansas)]</ref> The last Democratic candidate to carry the county was [[Jimmy Carter]] in 1976.<ref>[http://uselectionatlas.org/RESULTS/state.php?year=1976&fips=20&f=1&off=0&elect=0 David Leip's Presidential Election Atlas - 1976 statistics]</ref>\n\n===Laws===\nButler County was a prohibition, or [[dry county|\"dry\"]], county until the [[Kansas Constitution]] was amended in 1986 and voters approved the sale of alcoholic liquor by the individual drink with a 30% food sales requirement.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.ksrevenue.org/abcwetdrymap.htm |title=Map of Wet and Dry Counties |publisher=Alcoholic Beverage Control, Kansas Department of Revenue |date=November 2006 |accessdate=2007-12-26 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20071008013617/http://www.ksrevenue.org/abcwetdrymap.htm |archivedate=2007-10-08 }}</ref>\n\n==Education==\n\n===Unified school districts===\n* [[Bluestem USD 205]]\n* [[Remington USD 206]]\n* [[Circle USD 375]]\n* [[Andover USD 385]]\n* [[Rose Hill USD 394]]\n* [[Douglass USD 396]]\n* [[Augusta USD 402]]\n* [[El Dorado USD 490]]\n* [[Flinthills USD 492]]\n\n;District Office In Neighboring County\n* [[Peabody-Burns USD 398]]\n* [[Central USD 462]]\n\n===Private schools===\n* [[Berean Academy (Kansas)|Berean Academy]] in [[Elbing, Kansas|Elbing]]\n\n===College===\n* [[Butler County Community College (Kansas)|Butler County Community College]] in [[El Dorado, Kansas|El Dorado]]\n\n==Communities==\n[[File:Map of Butler Co, Ks, USA.png|thumb|300px|right|2005 [[Kansas Department of Transportation|KDOT]] Map of Butler County ([[:File:Kansas official transportation map legend.png|map legend]])]]\n\n===Cities===\n{{div col|colwidth=15em}}\n* [[Andover, Kansas|Andover]]\n* [[Augusta, Kansas|Augusta]]\n* [[Benton, Kansas|Benton]]\n* [[Cassoday, Kansas|Cassoday]]\n* [[Douglass, Kansas|Douglass]]\n* [[Elbing, Kansas|Elbing]]\n* [[El Dorado, Kansas|El Dorado]]\n* [[Latham, Kansas|Latham]]\n* [[Leon, Kansas|Leon]]\n* [[Potwin, Kansas|Potwin]]\n* [[Rose Hill, Kansas|Rose Hill]]\n* [[Towanda, Kansas|Towanda]]\n* [[Whitewater, Kansas|Whitewater]]\n{{div col end}}\n\n===Census-designated place===\n* [[Rosalia, Kansas|Rosalia]]\n\n===Other unincorporated places===\n{{div col|colwidth=15em}}\n* [[Beaumont, Kansas|Beaumont]]\n* [[Bois d'Arc, Kansas|Bois d'Arc]]\n* [[Brainerd, Kansas|Brainerd]]\n* Clay Center\n* [[De Graff, Kansas|De Graff]]\n* [[Gordon, Kansas|Gordon]]\n* [[Haverhill, Kansas|Haverhill]]\n* Hopkins\n* [[Keighley, Kansas|Keighley]]\n* Palmer\n* Pickrell Corner\n* [[Pontiac, Kansas|Pontiac]]\n* Prospect\n* Rock\n* Smileyberg\n{{div col end}}\n\n===Ghost towns===\n{{div col|colwidth=15em}}\n* Aikman\n* Alki\n* Amador\n* Browntown\n* Chelsea (now lies under El Dorado Lake)\n* Durachen\n* Frazier\n* Lorena\n* Magna City\n* Midian\n* [[Oil Hill, Kansas|Oil Hill]]\n* Oil Valley\n* Ophir\n* [[Plum Grove, Kansas|Plum Grove]]\n* Providence\n* Ramsey\n* Salter\n* Vanora\n* [[Wingate, Kansas|Wingate]]\n{{div col end}}\n\n===Townships===\nButler County is divided into twenty-nine [[Civil township|townships]]. The cities of [[Augusta, Kansas|Augusta]] and [[El Dorado, Kansas|El Dorado]] are considered ''governmentally independent'' and are excluded from the census figures for the townships. In the following table, the population center is the largest city (or cities) included in that township's population total, if it is of a significant size.\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align:center; font-size:90%; margin-bottom:0.25em; clear:both;\"\n|- style=\"background:#ccccff\"\n! Township !! [[FIPS place code|FIPS]] !! Population<br/>center\n! Population !! Population<br/>density<br/><small>/km\u00b2 (/sq&nbsp;mi)</small>\n! Land area<br/><small>km\u00b2 (sq&nbsp;mi)</small> !! Water area<br/><small>km\u00b2 (sq&nbsp;mi)</small> !! Water %\n! Geographic coordinates\n|- \n| Augusta || 03325 ||  || 1,405 || 17 (43) || 84 (32) || 1 (0) || 0.68% || {{coord|37|41|32|N|96|59|15|W|}} \n|- \n| Benton || 06200 || [[Benton, Kansas|Benton]] || 2,211 || 24 (61) || 93 (36) || 0 (0) || 0% || {{coord|37|47|0|N|97|6|11|W|}} \n|- \n| Bloomington || 07500 ||  || 544 || 6 (15) || 93 (36) || 0 (0) || 0% || {{coord|37|35|57|N|96|54|1|W|}} \n|- \n| Bruno || 08825 || [[Andover, Kansas|Andover]] || 9,744 || 107 (278) || 91 (35) || 0 (0) || 0.10% || {{coord|37|41|37|N|97|6|48|W|}} \n|- \n| Chelsea || 12750 ||  || 190 || 1 (2) || 261 (101) || 17 (7) || 6.15% || {{coord|37|55|27|N|96|44|34|W|}} \n|- \n| Clay || 13575 ||  || 83 || 1 (2) || 94 (36) || 0 (0) || 0.22% || {{coord|37|31|21|N|96|45|39|W|}} \n|- \n| Clifford || 14175 ||  || 259 || 2 (6) || 108 (42) || 0 (0) || 0.18% || {{coord|38|2|7|N|96|58|41|W|}} \n|- \n| Douglass || 18425 || [[Douglass, Kansas|Douglass]] || 2,306 || 25 (64) || 93 (36) || 0 (0) || 0.32% || {{coord|37|31|1|N|97|0|33|W|}} \n|- \n| El Dorado || 20100 ||  || 1,700 || 12 (32) || 140 (54) || 2 (1) || 1.46% || {{coord|37|48|38|N|96|52|23|W|}} \n|- \n| Fairmount || 22275 || [[Elbing, Kansas|Elbing]] || 511 || 5 (14) || 94 (36) || 0 